  "prompt": "Does a white background use more energy on a LCD than if it was set to black?",
  "response": "Yes, on LCD (Liquid Crystal Display) screens, a white background typically uses more energy than a black background. This is because LCD pixels require energy to block light from the backlight when displaying black, while white requires the full backlight to be on. \n\nHowever, this energy difference is more significant on older LCD technologies. Modern LED-backlit LCD screens have reduced this disparity, though a black background still generally uses slightly less power. \n\nOLED and AMOLED screens are different - on these display types, black pixels actually use no energy at all, so a black background can dramatically reduce power consumption.",
